{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504655"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:18:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:18:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2351"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2351"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.02,0.9,0.01,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2351"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107272"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2351"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2351"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89733"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1216"},{"type":"tags","id":"1279"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1332"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1427"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34737"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39203"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39611"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43131"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107272"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of pain in her right elbow. She works as a high-school janitor and the pain comes on after long hours of sweeping and mopping the floor. She is right-hand dominant. She does not recall any trauma or injury to her hand. She takes paracetamol prior to her work shift in anticipation of the pain, but she states that the pain medication is not effective. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her elbow has no skin deformities, redness or any masses observed. There is no reduced range of motion on elbow flexion or extension. However, she has tenderness on the lateral aspect of her elbow and the pain is worse during wrist extension and supination, particularly when these movements are resisted.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Olecranon bursitis","Medial epicondylitis","Lateral epicondylitis","Radial tunnel syndrome","Bicipital tendinitis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic features of lateral epicondylitis, commonly termed \u0022tennis elbow\u0022. The condition results from overuse of the common extensor tendon originating from the lateral epicondyle, causing microtears of the origin of the extensor carpi radialis brevis and/or extensor carpi radialis longus and extensor carpi ulnaris. This results in inflammation of the lateral epicondyle of the humerus. The condition is commonly precipitated by repetitive wrist extension and forearm supination, consistent with the patient\u0027s occupational activities as a janitor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral epicondylitis\u003C/strong\u003E produces pain on resisted supination, especially when trying to extend the wrist as well. This is because the lateral epicondyle is the origin of the common extensor muscles that extend and supinate the wrist. The lateral location of tenderness and specific pain with resisted wrist extension and supination are pathognomonic features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedial epicondylitis\u003C/strong\u003E (golfer\u0027s elbow) affects the medial epicondyle and common flexor tendon origin. Pain would be located medially and exacerbated by resisted wrist flexion and pronation, rather than the lateral pain with resisted extension and supination seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOlecranon bursitis\u003C/strong\u003E is the inflammation of the bursa overlying the olecranon process. This typically presents as redness, tenderness, and swelling over the posterior aspect of the elbow, which are not present in this case. The pain distribution and exacerbating factors also differ from lateral epicondylitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadial tunnel syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E involves compression of the posterior interosseous nerve as it passes through the radial tunnel. While it can cause lateral elbow pain, it typically presents with aching pain in the proximal forearm and weakness of finger extension, particularly the middle finger, rather than the specific pain pattern with resisted wrist movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBicipital tendinitis\u003C/strong\u003E involves inflammation of the biceps tendon and typically causes anterior elbow pain that worsens with resisted elbow flexion and forearm supination. The pain would be located anteriorly rather than laterally, and would not be specifically exacerbated by resisted wrist extension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELateral epicondylitis is commonly managed conservatively with modification of activity, NSAIDs for pain relief, and physical therapy. A counterforce brace can also be utilised to compress the extensor bundle, thus dampening and dispersing some of the force away from the extensor tendon origin. Non-operative management is very effective, though it may take time to achieve resolution.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Lateral epicondylitis (tennis elbow) is characterised by pain at the lateral epicondyle that worsens with resisted wrist extension and supination.","Lateral epicondylitis is commonly caused by repetitive microtrauma to the common extensor tendon origin.","Initial management of lateral epicondylitis includes activity modification, NSAIDs, physical therapy, and counterforce bracing."],"references":["Nirschl RP. The etiology and treatment of tennis elbow. J Sports Med 1974; 2:308.","De Smedt T, de Jong A, Van Leemput W, et al. Lateral epicondylitis in tennis: update on aetiology, biomechanics and treatment. Br J Sports Med 2007; 41:816.","Kroslak M, Pirapakaran K, Murrell G. Counterforce bracing of lateral epicondylitis: a prospective, randomized, double-blinded, placebo-controlled clinical trial. Journal of Shoulder and Elbow Surgery. 2019;28(2):288-295.","Zermansky AG. Clinical signs in elbow pain. Br J Gen Pract. 2015 Dec;65(641):628. doi: 10.3399/bjgp15X687745. PMID: 26622013; PMCID: PMC4655713. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4655713/#:~:text=Thus%20tennis%20elbow%20produces%20pain,extend%20and%20supinate%20the%20wrist."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89733"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2351"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89733"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-27T10:50:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-27T10:51:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2351"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107272"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,